~ Like taking candy from a baby

04:07.727 --> 04:11.402
- ~ A, B, C
- ~ A, B, C

04:11.487 --> 04:14.285
~ Falling in love with you was

04:14.967 --> 04:16.958
~ Easy for me

04:18.647 --> 04:21.081
~ And you can do it, too

04:21.166 --> 04:24.125
- ~ Its easy
- ~ It`s so easy

04:24.207 --> 04:27.438
~ Like taking candy from a baby

04:27.527 --> 04:31.679
Hi. I'm Glenn Holland.
I'm the new music teacher.

04:32.087 --> 04:33.805
Vice Principal Wolters.

04:35.087 --> 04:37.078
Holy cow!

04:38.927 --> 04:40.519
- A Corvair.
- Yeah.

04:40.607 --> 04:43.360
I take it you didn"t read
Ralph Nader"s book.

04:43.447 --> 04:46.439
Well, unless Ralph
is willing to buy me a new car,

04:46.527 --> 04:49.917
I'm gonna have to stick with this one
until the wheels fall off.

04:50.007 --> 04:53.204
Well, you may not have to
wait that long. Heh-heh.

04:54.927 --> 04:57.521
- Have a nice day.
- Thanks.

04:57.607 --> 05:00.440
- ~ Its easy
- ~ It`s so easy

05:00.527 --> 05:04.520
~ Like taking candy from a baby

05:05.007 --> 05:06.998
You look lost, Mr Holland.

05:08.447 --> 05:11.166
Helen Jacobs. Remember? I hired you.

05:11.247 --> 05:13.442
Oh!

05:13.527 --> 05:18.999
Of course you did. I'm sorry. It was not
that I'm lost. I was just looking for the...

05:19.087 --> 05:23.000
- Well, yes, of course I'm lost.
- What an auspicious beginning.

05:23.567 --> 05:25.558
This way.

05:26.047 --> 05:29.403
Your first day as a teacher,
Mr Holland. Excited?

05:29.487 --> 05:32.638
Nervous. Boy, I never thought I"d be here.

05:32.727 --> 05:34.843
No? Why not?

05:34.927 --> 05:38.237
Well... like most people,
I only got my teaching certificate

05:38.327 --> 05:40.682
so I"d have something to fall back on.

05:40.767 --> 05:43.565
This isn't a drive-in, Mr Claridge.
Hands off!

05:43.647 --> 05:47.925
You know, Mr Holland, I don't think
of teaching as a fallback position.

05:48.007 --> 05:50.840
- No, no...
- I grow nervous around people who do.

05:50.927 --> 05:53.885
I'm... I'm really very happy
to be here. Really.

05:53.967 --> 05:59.439
Good. You"ll drop by my office later on.
I have a list of students you"ll be advising.

05:59.527 --> 06:04.078
Advising? Can I ask when
I'm supposed to be doing this advising?

06:04.167 --> 06:08.126
that's for you and the student to arrange.
You meet your orchestra when?

06:08.207 --> 06:10.198
Fifth period.

06:11.407 --> 06:13.557
- Are they any good?
- They try hard.

06:13.647 --> 06:17.526
By the way, I'll need a complete
lesson plan from you by Friday.

06:18.087 --> 06:20.203
- Right.
- For September and October.

06:20.287 --> 06:21.436
Right.

06:32.527 --> 06:34.245
(door opens)

06:44.287 --> 06:46.278
(school bell)

06:59.847 --> 07:03.965
All right. People, come on,
let"s take our seats a little quicker, please.

07:04.047 --> 07:07.756
A little quicker. We"re losing time.
Come on in, come on in.

07:07.847 --> 07:09.838
My name is Mr Holland.

07:10.967 --> 07:15.245
This, of course, is a title of courtesy
that I will extend back to you -

07:15.487 --> 07:19.036
"Mr" or "Miss",
as the circumstances allow.

07:19.127 --> 07:21.118
Welcome to Music Appreciation.

07:21.207 --> 07:26.520
This is a class in which we will be
studying the history of music.

07:26.607 --> 07:30.725
Um, who would like to give me
a definition of what music is?

07:32.447 --> 07:34.438
Any music. What do you think?

07:35.487 --> 07:40.800
What do they think that music is
in... in general? What do they think?

07:40.887 --> 07:42.878
Anybody?

07:44.567 --> 07:46.558
Nobody?

07:47.087 --> 07:51.365
OK. Let"s, uh... let"s go to the text.

07:52.167 --> 07:56.524
And we turn to page, um... four.

07:56.607 --> 08:04.924
And we read that "Music is sound
in melodic or harmonic combinations,

08:05.007 --> 08:07.680
whether produced
by voice or instrument. "

08:09.047 --> 08:11.038
Now, questions?

08:12.047 --> 08:14.277
Anybody... at all?

08:17.167 --> 08:19.044
No?

08:19.127 --> 08:20.037
Hm?

08:20.127 --> 08:21.799
Good.

08:21.887 --> 08:23.764
All righty, uh...

08:23.847 --> 08:30.685
Now, I just... you know, I just...
want you all to relax, have a little fun.

08:30.767 --> 08:33.486
We"re not here to impress each other.

08:33.567 --> 08:36.034
OK. All right, let"s get ready.

08:38.246 --> 08:40.238
Everyone? Come on.

08:43.167 --> 08:45.556
You ready?

08:46.087 --> 08:48.078
OK, here we go.

08:48.527 --> 08:51.837
(~ discordant `Symphony No 5
in C Minor``` by Beethoven)

09:33.967 --> 09:35.639
It was good.

09:35.727 --> 09:38.366
Miss Aronson.
Would you stand up, please?

09:39.207 --> 09:41.004
Stand up, please.

09:41.087 --> 09:46.081
Is that skirt regulation length?
On your knees, both of you, right now.

09:47.247 --> 09:51.240
I thought so. Come with me to the
principal"s office. You are going home.

09:51.327 --> 09:53.795
You can come back
when you"re dressed properly.

09:53.887 --> 09:55.639
- You"re not being fair.
- I am.

09:55.727 --> 09:58.639
If I allow you to do it,
everyone is allowed to do it.

09:58.727 --> 10:00.922
- Hi.
- Hi.

10:03.127 --> 10:05.118
Come on, out of my way.

10:07.367 --> 10:10.677
- Teachers don't wait.
- Pardon me?

10:10.767 --> 10:13.679
High school is not a democracy.
Teachers don't wait.

10:13.767 --> 10:15.883
Bill Meister. Phys ed.

10:15.967 --> 10:18.606
- Glenn Holland. Music teacher.
- Hi.

10:22.287 --> 10:25.279
- There you go.
- Oh, my God!

10:25.367 --> 10:29.280
- What is this?
- It's Monday. It's Turkey Spam Surprise.

10:29.847 --> 10:31.883
You could mortar walls with it.

10:31.967 --> 10:34.879
Word of advice: always bring a bag lunch.

10:34.967 --> 10:37.435
- Where"s yours?
- I ate it in second period.

10:37.527 --> 10:40.519
Sylvie! don't tease me. I need extra.

10:41.087 --> 10:43.647
So what have you been doin"
for the last ten years?

10:43.727 --> 10:46.719
I've been playing music.
Been on the road.

10:46.807 --> 10:51.961
You know, um... clubs and weddings
and bar mitzvahs. That sort of thing.

10:52.047 --> 10:55.926
Wait a minute. I bet you met
a ton of chicks in those clubs, huh?

10:56.007 --> 10:59.363
So you"re in these clubs,
there are all these women there...

10:59.447 --> 11:02.041
- Why"d you become a teacher?
- Well...

11:02.127 --> 11:04.880
Actually, I started teaching
because I was hoping

11:04.967 --> 11:09.165
it would give me some free time to do
some composing. I'm a composer.

11:12.527 --> 11:15.200
- What? what's so funny?
- Oh, the free time.

11:17.367 --> 11:20.803
Glenn, I can't remember
the last time I had that was free.

11:45.927 --> 11:47.918
(Iris) I've got it all figured out.

11:48.007 --> 11:51.158
With your salary, plus what I take in
with the photography,

11:51.247 --> 11:53.681
in four years we should have
enough for you to quit

11:53.767 --> 11:58.921
and do nothing but compose music
and become famous and make us rich.

11:59.007 --> 12:02.238
- I'll never make it.
- I made us $32 today.

12:02.327 --> 12:06.445
Big deal. I made 32 kids
sleep with their eyes open.

12:06.527 --> 12:08.518
Oh, right there! Yeah.

12:09.527 --> 12:11.961
Right there. Yeah.

12:16.607 --> 12:22.045
Iris... I think this is gonna be
a lot rougher gig than I originally thought.

12:25.047 --> 12:30.075
You know, when I was in high school...
I wanted to be someplace else, you know.

12:30.167 --> 12:32.044
Anyplace.

12:32.127 --> 12:36.086
It never occurred to me that
my teachers would feel the same way.

12:36.887 --> 12:39.447
Well... you can still quit.

12:39.527 --> 12:44.442
- Nah. We"ve been through all that.
- The band"s getting pretty good.

12:44.527 --> 12:47.246
We could play Holiday Inns
for the rest of our lives.

12:47.327 --> 12:51.366
- Or Los Angeles.
- I don't wanna be a studio musician.

12:52.327 --> 12:54.477
So, It's four years" teaching, then.

12:59.487 --> 13:01.478
Come here.

13:07.807 --> 13:09.798
When you were in high school...

13:10.367 --> 13:13.564
did you ever wonder
if your teachers got it on at night?

13:13.647 --> 13:17.526
When I was in high school
my teachers were all priests and nuns.

13:18.647 --> 13:23.960
I had such a crush on Mr Griffith.
He could"ve taken me home any time.

13:24.047 --> 13:26.277
- Really?
- Mm-hm.

13:26.367 --> 13:28.676
And who was this Mr Griffith?

13:28.767 --> 13:32.043
Oh... he was my music teacher.

13:37.087 --> 13:39.157
(~ woodwind section plays)

13:49.687 --> 13:51.678
(~ discordant notes)

13:55.407 --> 13:57.045
OK. OK.

13:57.127 --> 13:59.925
That wasn't bad. That wasn't bad at all.

14:00.007 --> 14:02.282
- Miss...? I'm sorry.
- Lang.

14:02.367 --> 14:04.927
- Pardon me?
- Lang. Gertrude Lang.

14:05.687 --> 14:11.762
OK. Miss Lang, um... would you
take it from bar 37, please?

14:21.527 --> 14:23.518
(~ discordant notes)

14:31.327 --> 14:32.999
(whispering and giggling)

14:33.087 --> 14:34.600
OK. OK.

14:34.687 --> 14:37.918
- (school bell)
- Good. Good. that's enough for today.

14:38.007 --> 14:40.680
I'll see you all tomorrow. Very good work.

14:40.767 --> 14:44.237
Miss Lang? Would you mind
hanging for a moment, please?

14:52.407 --> 14:55.797
You seem to be having a little trouble
getting through the break.

14:55.887 --> 14:58.003
I know.

14:58.087 --> 15:00.840
- How long have you been playing?
- Three years.

15:02.367 --> 15:04.676
Really?

15:04.767 --> 15:06.166
Uh...

15:06.247 --> 15:09.205
Do you find that you get
all the practice time that you need?

15:09.287 --> 15:11.676
I practise constantly, yeah.

15:15.047 --> 15:17.038
Well...

15:18.047 --> 15:22.359
then I think... I think maybe
you and I should find some time

15:22.447 --> 15:24.597
to work on an individual basis.

15:24.687 --> 15:27.406
- That would be great.
- I don't have a lot of time, but...

15:27.487 --> 15:31.719
that's OK. Whatever you can give me.
I really, really wanna do good at this.

15:31.807 --> 15:33.798
I bet you do. Um...

15:34.407 --> 15:39.925
Well, come in about a half-hour before
first period tomorrow and we"ll just start...

15:40.007 --> 15:44.159
OK. All right. Thank you...
thank you very much. Thanks.

16:11.007 --> 16:15.319
When a flat precedes a note, like this,

16:15.407 --> 16:19.923
it indicates that the note
is to be played a half-step lower.

16:20.887 --> 16:22.798
A piece based in F major

16:22.887 --> 16:26.323
should have a flat sign
at the beginning of every stave.

17:25.607 --> 17:28.644
These tests... are pathetic.

17:32.767 --> 17:35.486
"Name an American composer. "

17:35.567 --> 17:38.957
Miss Swedlin, your answer was...?

17:39.047 --> 17:40.526
"Bach"?

17:40.607 --> 17:43.075
"Johann Sebastian Bach. "

17:45.367 --> 17:47.517
Oh, this is my favourite one.

17:47.607 --> 17:51.725
"How do you know
what key a concerto is in?"

17:52.607 --> 17:58.762
Mr Mims, your answer was
"Look on the front page?"

17:59.847 --> 18:03.681
Now, this question mark -
was that because you weren"t sure?

18:03.767 --> 18:08.477
Or because your English skills are on
the same level as your musical theory?

18:08.567 --> 18:12.003
These tests are a waste
of my time, and yours!

18:12.087 --> 18:15.045
No kidding! I"d rather be somewhere else.

18:15.127 --> 18:19.200
Mr Sullivan! Why don't you pay a visit
to Mr Wolters, right now!

18:19.287 --> 18:21.562
Get your books and get outta here!

18:25.287 --> 18:28.597
As for the rest of you,
get your textbooks out.

18:28.687 --> 18:33.363
We"re gonna go over these answers
one by one until you get them right.

18:33.447 --> 18:35.438
(school bell)

18:55.087 --> 18:57.078
(~ discordant clarinet)

19:06.047 --> 19:08.322
Give it up, Miss Lang.

19:10.847 --> 19:12.838
(sobbing)

19:34.087 --> 19:36.078
I meant for the day.

19:36.727 --> 19:39.719
- I meant "Give it up for the day. "
- I know what you meant.

19:39.807 --> 19:42.401
Then... why are you crying?

19:42.487 --> 19:44.478
I'm terrible. I'm...

19:45.087 --> 19:49.638
I'm terrible. I practise till my lips swell up,
but all I make is noise.

19:49.727 --> 19:52.161
It takes work
to learn a musical instrument.

19:52.247 --> 19:55.319
I just... I just wanna be good at something.

19:55.767 --> 19:59.123
My sister"s got a ballet scholarship
to go to Juilliard,

19:59.207 --> 20:03.644
and my brother"s going to Notre Dame
on a football scholarship.

20:03.727 --> 20:07.276
My mother"s won the blue ribbon
for watercolours at the state fair

20:07.367 --> 20:09.927
so many times
they"ve retired the category.

20:10.007 --> 20:13.158
My father"s got the most
beautiful voice. he's...

20:15.727 --> 20:18.116
I'm the only one in my family who"s...

20:19.127 --> 20:21.561
I... I just can't...

20:22.327 --> 20:23.760
(sobbing)

20:23.847 --> 20:26.600
It doesn't make any difference anyway. I...

20:33.567 --> 20:36.479
Mr Holland!
Just the man I was looking for.

20:36.567 --> 20:39.127
We"re forming a textbook committee
for next year.

20:39.207 --> 20:43.564
I would like to have your suggestions. We
meet next Tuesday night in the library.

20:43.647 --> 20:46.764
Oh, I'm sorry, Mrs Jacobs.
I'm very busy on Tuesday night.

20:46.847 --> 20:48.485
Uh-huh?

20:48.567 --> 20:52.162
You know, for a good four or five months
now, I've been watching you.

20:52.247 --> 20:55.444
I've never seen a teacher
sprint for the parking lot

20:55.527 --> 20:58.121
with more speed and enthusiasm
than his students.

20:58.207 --> 21:00.516
Perhaps you should be our track coach.

21:00.607 --> 21:04.520
Mrs Jacobs, I get here on time
every morning, don't I?

21:04.607 --> 21:06.882
I'm doing my job the best I can.

21:07.007 --> 21:11.000
A teacher is two jobs.
Fill young minds with knowledge, yes.

21:11.087 --> 21:14.318
But, more important,
give those minds a compass

21:14.407 --> 21:16.398
so that knowledge doesn't go to waste.

21:16.487 --> 21:18.876
I don't know what you do
with the knowledge,

21:18.967 --> 21:21.435
but as a compass, you"re stuck.

21:26.327 --> 21:31.196
I really hate that woman!
And I hate teaching, Iris. I hate it.

21:31.287 --> 21:33.801
Nobody could teach
these children. Nobody!

21:34.127 --> 21:36.243
I don't know what I'm gonna do.

21:36.327 --> 21:41.606
They just sit there, staring up at me.
there's no there there. I've been trying...

21:41.687 --> 21:45.441
You played a lot of tough houses.
When they didn"t listen, did you quit?

21:45.527 --> 21:49.679
Wait a minute. Wait a minute! Aren"t we
supposed to be on the same side?

21:49.767 --> 21:51.485
I am.

21:51.567 --> 21:53.558
It's just that I...

21:54.247 --> 21:56.203
I...

21:56.887 --> 21:58.957
- (sighs)
- What?

22:01.967 --> 22:03.958
I'm pregnant.

22:05.927 --> 22:13.766
I wasn't... I wasn't sure if I was,
but I went to the doctor and I... I am.

22:16.687 --> 22:18.678
We are.

22:22.687 --> 22:24.678
S...

22:25.207 --> 22:27.038
Say something.

22:32.487 --> 22:34.842
Wow.

22:56.047 --> 22:58.038
Iris...

22:58.807 --> 23:03.403
- Iris...
- I... I don't know. I knew!

23:03.487 --> 23:08.959
- I knew you wouldn"t be, but I just...
- Iris, it just took me by surprise, that's all.

23:15.807 --> 23:18.275
Let me tell you a story, OK?

23:20.447 --> 23:24.918
When I was 15 years old
I used to hang out at a local record store.

23:25.007 --> 23:29.637
There was this guy who worked there
who thought he knew what I liked,

23:29.727 --> 23:34.164
and he handed me this album one day
and it was John Coltrane.

23:36.007 --> 23:38.726
So I took it home
and I put it on the machine.

23:39.407 --> 23:42.638
And I hated it. I mean, I really hated it.

23:43.047 --> 23:45.083
I just didn"t get it.

23:46.687 --> 23:50.236
So I... played it again.

23:51.287 --> 23:53.881
I played it again, and I played it again...

23:55.007 --> 23:59.444
and then... I just couldn"t stop playin" it.

24:01.807 --> 24:04.196
I kept listening to those notes.

24:06.527 --> 24:13.046
And I realised that... that's what
I wanted to do with the rest of my life.

24:14.207 --> 24:16.198
You know?

24:17.287 --> 24:19.278
Make music.

24:32.167 --> 24:34.158
What am I tryin" to say?

24:36.647 --> 24:38.717
Look, Iris...

24:38.807 --> 24:43.835
Look, you... you tell me that...
we"re gonna have a baby.

24:45.847 --> 24:47.838
Well...

24:50.047 --> 24:54.518
that's like... falling in love
with John Coltrane...

24:56.487 --> 24:58.478
all over again.

25:03.167 --> 25:07.718
If that is a lie,
that is the sweetest lie I ever heard.

25:16.647 --> 25:19.559
- (school bell)
- Let"s take our seats, please.

25:22.327 --> 25:27.037
Anybody here know the difference
between the lonian and the Dorian scale?

25:27.767 --> 25:29.758
Anybody?

25:30.807 --> 25:32.206
(chuckles)

25:32.287 --> 25:34.278
I just wanted to confirm the fact

25:34.367 --> 25:39.122
that I've made absolutely no impact
on you in the last five months.

25:41.207 --> 25:43.675
- Mr Sullivan.
- Yeah.

25:45.127 --> 25:47.960
What kind of music
do you like to listen to?

25:48.047 --> 25:50.800
- Um...
- don't be afraid.

25:53.127 --> 25:54.879
Rock"n"roll.

25:54.967 --> 25:57.322
- What about you?
- Rock"n"roll.

26:00.047 --> 26:02.515
- You?
- Classical.

26:02.607 --> 26:04.882
- Brown-noser.
- (laughter)

26:06.087 --> 26:08.681
Does anybody here like
Johann Sebastian Bach?

26:09.567 --> 26:11.683
Other than you?

26:11.767 --> 26:17.080
I'll bet all of you, whether you know it or
not, already like Johann Sebastian Bach.

26:17.567 --> 26:20.035
(~ `A Lover`s Concerto```)

26:24.487 --> 26:27.524
- what's this called?
- (all) "A Lover's Concerto".

26:28.247 --> 26:30.886
- Who wrote it?
- The Toys.

26:30.967 --> 26:32.161
Wrong!

26:32.247 --> 26:38.117
That was "Minuet in G", and it was written
by Johann Sebastian Bach.

26:38.207 --> 26:40.198
(~ `Minuet in G Major``` by Bach)

26:44.567 --> 26:46.558
Can you hear it?

